<Review ID>4133539
<Product Name>iRiver CXW-2G Clix 2 GB Digital Music and Video Player, White
<Title>Problems galore.
<Date>Mon Nov 27 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>Like some others that have left reviews here, I tried to love this thing. I really did. It got great reviews in most places. Its small, has great sound, and has a nice crisp screen (and is really nifty looking). BUT. That's where it ends. Feature-wise, iRiver really didn't go all out.   Strike one: if you're an avid ogg fan, you get the short end of the stick: the clix does not support ogg tags. This makes it difficult, if not impossible, to make playlists while the DAP is not hooked up to a computer. You can't just select 'Add to Quick List' (which is handy if you're away from a computer and want to make a temporary playlist, and if, of course, you're using anything that's readable through tags). The tags are what organize this DAP, not the filenames that you transfer over. That ogg tags are not supported makes using this DAP difficult if most of your library is made up of ogg.   Strike two: the fact that they don't emphasize that you absolutely, positively NEED Windows Media Player 10 or higher to get onto this DAP borders on false advertising. I mean, this thing is USELESS if you don't have Windows. It might as well be used as a paperweight. This, coupled the clix's dependence on Windows'/WMP's use of Media Transfer Protocol, is like finding an anti-usability ceiling above one's head: you have to finangle it JUST RIGHT and depend on faulty software to make it work. There is NO OTHER OPTION.  Strike three: that OTHER PEOPLE (*cough*iriverter*cough*) had to write software to convert videos to the proper format instead of the iRiver support/software team just shows me how they seem to be lacking customer support. I leave others to draw their own conclusions, but for this guy, it seems not a whole lot to ask for something so important to the success of the product.   I guess I bought this little DAP before really hearing out the negatives that people had to say. It just seemed so... nifty. With this review, I'm trying to warn people looking for functionality about what this DAP truly lacks. If you have mostly id3 tagged mp3s this thing might be for you. I can't say anything about wma, because I've stayed as far away from them as I possibly can. Just be forewarned, the fact that it supports the ogg format doesn't mean that it supports everything that comes with oggs; the fact that it is backed by Microsoft doesn't mean that its user-friendly; and be wary of the customer support. *rant over*  
<Overall>1

<Review ID>1387180
<Product Name>iRiver CXW-2G Clix 2 GB Digital Music and Video Player, White
<Title>It Rocks!!
<Date>Thu Nov 30 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>This cute little thing rocks. The graphic equalizer allows you to adjust the sound to your taste. The graphics are colorful and crisp. I personalized mine by putting a picture of myself, titled with my phone number just in case it is lost, in it. (Between you and I, I don't expect that anyone will really return something that's so cool.) The interface is very intuitive. The only things that gave me trouble are Windows Media Player (WMP) and the earphones. First off, I've own the iRiver 795 (absolutely, loved it) and the T30 (hated it). The 795 supported UMS, which was great because I could just create folders of music on my computer and drag and drop them onto the player via the USB port. Well, the T30 is a little bitty player, that is difficult to use and did not, like the Clix, support UMS well at all. When you drag and drop folders into them, the folders (playlists) are discarded and songs are just loaded into the player in alphabetical order. With the T30, I was so frustrated that I wouldn't take the time to learn to use WMP. The Clix, however, was so enthralling that I was not only willing to learn to use the program, but also figured it out in 30 minutes. Patience! All you have to do is drag and drop your music folders into the Clix window that opens in WMP after you attach the Clix to your computer with the USB cable, open WMP, then open the player. You will see a picture of the Clix. Create a playlist or folder via the dropdown menu within the Clix window, save the playlist. Clear the playlist from the Clix window via the dropdown menu. When you are ready to sync the playlists to the Clix,  drag all of your new playlists back to the sync window and click 'sync'. All of your playlists will sync to the Clix quickly. If you only have one playlist to sync, then there is no need to save the playlist first, unless you want to save it to WMP (recommended).   Now, for the earphones: they do not fit my small ear canals at all. Luckily I had a pair of Sonys already. To get the most out of the Clix, I've order a pair a Shure E4G earphones. Also, you might want to go to eBay an buy a protective overlay (generic) for the player interface. The interface is a fingerprint magnet. Lastly, if you own an old iRiver, use the neckstrap from it by attaching it to the Clix case. Also, there is a 4GB model available.  
<Overall>5

